Your client is struggling to understand why MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error) is higher for P&C despite its lower loss amounts and event frequency. To help clarify this, letâ€™s break it down with strong evidence, notes, and visual explanations.

ğŸ“Œ Key Reasons Why MAPE is High for P&C
Lower Event Count Causes High Sensitivity to Errors

Banking has a large number of events, meaning small prediction errors get averaged out.
P&C has fewer events, so even small absolute errors translate to high percentage errors.
Example:
Banking: Actual Loss = $10M, Predicted Loss = $9.8M â†’ MAPE = 2%
P&C: Actual Loss = $500K, Predicted Loss = $450K â†’ MAPE = 10%
Same absolute error ($50K) â†’ Higher % impact for P&C due to smaller actual values.
Higher Variability in Losses for P&C

Banking losses tend to be more consistent over time.
P&C losses are sporadic, meaning some months have very low losses, and some have extreme spikes.
Monte Carlo struggles with highly volatile distributions â†’ Higher error variance.
Impact of Loss Distribution Shape

Banking follows a smooth, normal-like distribution â†’ Easier to estimate.
P&C has a skewed, heavy-tailed distribution â†’ Harder for Monte Carlo to simulate accurately.
More extreme, rare events in P&C make predictions less stable.
Higher Coefficient of Variation (CV) for P&C

CV = Standard Deviation / Mean
Higher CV means higher unpredictability â†’ Monte Carlo struggles.
