In P&C, many losses are small (e.g., $200K - $1M).
Even a small absolute error in prediction becomes a large percentage error.
ğŸ“Œ Example:

Actual Loss ($)	Monte Carlo Prediction ($)	Absolute Error ($)	MAPE (%)
500K	1.2M	700K	140%
2M	3M	1M	50%
10M	9M	1M	10%
âœ… Evidence:
ğŸ”¹ Plot MAPE vs. Net Loss Amount â†’ Small losses have high MAPE.
ğŸ”¹ Compare MAPE across different loss percentiles.

ğŸ” 3ï¸âƒ£ Issue: Small Sample Size in P&C
Monte Carlo needs a large sample of events to estimate probabilities accurately.
P&C has fewer historical loss events, leading to unstable predictions.
Small sample sizes lead to high variance in Monte Carlo estimates, which inflates MAPE.
ğŸ“Œ Example:
ğŸ”¹ Banking: 10,000 events â†’ Monte Carlo generates stable predictions â†’ Low MAPE.
ğŸ”¹ P&C: 50 events â†’ Monte Carlo struggles â†’ High MAPE.

âœ… Evidence:
ğŸ”¹ Compare Monte Carlo predictions across different sample sizes.

ğŸ” 4ï¸âƒ£ Issue: Monte Carlo Assumes a Distribution That Doesn't Fit P&C
Monte Carlo assumes a known probability distribution (e.g., Normal, Lognormal).
P&C losses are not normally distributed â†’ They have a fat tail (extreme losses).
Monte Carlo struggles to capture extreme tail risks accurately, leading to bias in predictions.
âœ… Evidence:
ğŸ”¹ Fit different probability distributions to P&C losses and compare them.
ğŸ”¹ Use Quantile-Quantile (Q-Q) plots to check Monte Carlo's distribution fit.

ğŸ“Œ Alternative Solution: What to Do Instead?
âœ… Use Historical Simulation instead of Monte Carlo â†’ Uses real loss data instead of assuming a distribution.
âœ… Use Extreme Value Theory (EVT) for rare P&C losses â†’ Models extreme events separately.
âœ… Use Bootstrapping to generate alternative risk scenarios â†’ More stable than Monte Carlo for small datasets.

ğŸ“Š How to Explain This to the Client
âœ” Monte Carlo works well for stable distributions (Banking) but fails for P&C because:

High variance â†’ Inflates errors.
Small losses â†’ Cause high percentage errors.
Small sample size â†’ Leads to unstable predictions.
Incorrect distribution assumption â†’ Skews results.
âœ” Switching to Historical Simulation or EVT will provide more reliable VaR estimates.
